Create a new project: gitlab-prefix-verifier — a small Kubernetes
operator that automates "protected prefix" stamping for the
kro-argocd-tenant platform. Read that repo's README/AGENTS.md for
context: mgmt namespaces carry platform-guarded identity labels
(example.com/tenant) and an example.com/protected-prefixes JSON-array
annotation that admission policies treat as the source of truth for
tenant-exclusive GitLab prefixes. Today the platform stamps it
manually; this operator takes over. Its SA must simply be added to
the existing allowed-stampers policy list — do not redesign that
contract.

1. CRD: GitLabPrefixClaim (namespaced — lives in the tenant's mgmt
   namespace):
   spec:
     prefix: string            # normalized URL prefix being claimed
     proofTokenSecretRef:      # Secret in the SAME namespace holding
       name/key                # a maintainer-level GitLab token
   status:
     phase: Pending|Verified|Failed|Stale
     reason, lastVerified, observedGeneration
   Normalization rules must match the platform's (https, lowercase
   host, no trailing slash, no .git) — validate and normalize on
   reconcile; reject non-conforming prefixes with a clear status.

2. RECONCILE (controller-runtime, Go):
   - Resolve the group/sub-group path from the prefix; call the
     GitLab API using ONLY the claim's proof token (the operator
     holds no standing GitLab credentials — per-claim tokens only).
   - Verify the token's effective access level on that exact group is
     Maintainer (40) or Owner (50) — inherited membership counts;
     access to a parent group does NOT verify a claim on a different
     subtree; access to only a sub-group does NOT verify the parent.
   - Cross-tenant exclusivity: before stamping, list all mgmt
     namespaces (label example.com/tenant exists) and reject if the
     prefix equals/prefixes/is-prefixed-by any prefix already stamped
     on a DIFFERENT tenant's namespace (defense in depth — admission
     also checks overlap, but the operator must not race it).
   - On success: append the prefix to the claim's namespace
     example.com/protected-prefixes annotation (JSON array,
     de-duplicated, SSA with a dedicated field manager) and set
     status Verified.
   - On failure: status Failed with an actionable reason (token
     invalid / insufficient access level / wrong group / overlap).

3. RE-VERIFICATION:
   - Re-check Verified claims on a configurable interval (default
     24h). On lost maintainership or dead token: set Stale (do NOT
     auto-remove the stamp — the platform's referential policy blocks
     unstamping while repo-creds exist; removal is a human/alerted
     act). Emit a Kubernetes Event and a metric on every transition.
   - Claim deletion: remove the prefix from the annotation IFF no
     ArgoCDProjectRepository repo-creds instance in that namespace
     still uses it; otherwise block via finalizer with a status
     message (mirror the platform's one-directional referential
     rule — never create a cycle).

4. SECURITY:
   - RBAC: get/list/watch GitLabPrefixClaims + Secrets ONLY in
     namespaces labeled example.com/tenant; patch Namespaces
     (annotation only — document that field-level restriction isn't
     enforceable in RBAC, so keep the controller minimal and audited);
     events. Nothing cluster-write beyond that.
   - Never log tokens; proof tokens are read per-reconcile, never
     cached to disk.
   - Rate-limit GitLab API calls; exponential backoff on 429/5xx.

5. TESTS: envtest for reconcile paths (verified, insufficient
   access, parent/sub-group mismatch, overlap rejection, stale
   transition, deletion-with-finalizer); a fake GitLab API server for
   unit tests; document a manual e2e checklist against a real GitLab
   group.

6. DELIVERY: Dockerfile, kustomize deploy manifests (namespace,
   RBAC, deployment), metrics endpoint, README covering: the stamp
   contract it fulfills, the one-line platform change to activate it
   (add its SA to allowed-stampers), and the runbook for Stale
   claims.
